To convert Markdown-formatted text to HTML-formatted text in C++, you can use a third-party library like Boost.ICU or Gumbo. However, if you prefer to write your own implementation, you can use a combination of regular expressions and string manipulations.

Here's a basic example implementation of such a function using the Boost.Regex library:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <boost/regex.hpp>
#include <utility> // std::forward

namespace {

// Helper functions to format Markdown-specific elements to HTML.
std::string formatBold(const std::string& text) {
    return "<strong>" + text + "</strong>";
}

std::string formatItalic(const std::string& text) {
    return "<em>" + text + "</em>";
}

std::string formatLink(const std::string& text, const std::string& href) {
    return "<a href=\"" + href + "\">" + text + "</a>";
}

} // namespace anonymous

std::string markdownToHtml(std::string& markdownText) {
    // Define regular expressions for common Markdown elements.
    const boost::regex markdownLinkRegex{"\\[([^\\]]*)\\]\\(([^\\)]*)\\)"};
    const boost::regex markdownBoldRegex{"\\*([^\\*]*)\\*"};
    const boost::regex markdownItalicRegex{"_([^_]*)_"};

    // Replace Markdown elements with their corresponding HTML tags.
    std::string htmlText;
    boost::smatch match;
    while (boost::regex_search(markdownText.begin(), markdownText.end(), match, markdownLinkRegex)) {
        const std::string linkText = match[1];
        const std::string linkHref = match[2];
        htmlText += formatLink(linkText, linkHref) + " "; // add space after link for better formatting
        markdownText.erase(match.position(), match.length()); // remove matched substring from original text
    }

    while (boost::regex_search(markdownText.begin(), markdownText.end(), match, markdownBoldRegex)) {
        const std::string boldText = match[1];
        htmlText += formatBold(boldText) + " "; // add space after bold text for better formatting
        markdownText.erase(match.position(), match.length()); // remove matched substring from original text
    }

    while (boost::regex_search(markdownText.begin(), markdownText.end(), match, markdownItalicRegex)) {
        const std::string italicText = match[1];
        htmlText += formatItalic(italicText) + " "; // add space after italic text for better formatting
        markdownText.erase(match.position(), match.length()); // remove matched substring from original text
    }

    htmlText.erase(htmlText.find_last_not_noexcept(' ') + 1); // remove last space character (if any) from HTML result string

    return std::move(htmlText); // return converted string by move semantics for efficiency reasons.
}
```

To use this function, you can pass a reference to your Markdown-formatted string like this:

```cpp
std::string markdownText = R"(This is *bold* text and _italic_. [Link Text](https://example.com))"; // Example Markdown string with bold, italic, and link elements. 
std::cout << "Markdown input:\n" << markdownText << '\n'; // Print original Markdown input for debugging purposes. 
auto htmlResult = markdownToHtml(std::forward<decltype(markdownText)>(markdownText)); // Convert Markdown to HTML using our function. 
std::cout << "HTML output:\n" << htmlResult << '\n'; // Print resulting HTML formatted text for debugging purposes. 
``` 

Note that this implementation assumes that your Markdown-formatted string does not contain nested HTML tags or other advanced features like tables or fenced code blocks. If you need more advanced handling, you may want to consider using a third-party library like Boost.ICU or Gumbo instead.

