Here's a Java solution:

```java
public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
    if (n <= 0 || (n & (n - 1)) != 0) { // negative numbers and non-power-of-three numbers have a least significant bit set
        return false;
    }

    int log3 = 0;
    while ((n >> log3) > 0) { // perform right shift operations until n becomes less than or equal to 3^log3
        n >>>= 1; // divide by 3 (equivalent to right shift by 1)
        log3++;
    }

    return n == 1 || (log3 % 3) == 0; // check if n is now 1 or the logarithm base 3 is divisible by 3 (i.e., n is a power of three)
}
```

The approach works as follows:

1. Check if `n` is negative or has a least significant bit set (not a power of three). Return `false` in this case.
2. Initialize `log3` to 0. Perform right shifts until `n` becomes less than or equal to `3^log3`. Each right shift operation divides `n` by 3. After this loop, `log3` will hold the largest power-of-three exponent that `n` can be expressed as.
3. Check if `n` is now equal to 1 (a power of three with exponent 0), or if the exponent `log3` is divisible by 3. If either of these conditions hold, then `n` is a power of three.

This algorithm has a time complexity of O(log n) and a space complexity of O(1).

